title: For Sale:  $25.000 M41 PULSE RIFLE
postcontent:
Lightweight and rugged, the M41 is constructed largely from ultra-light alloy precision metal stampings, with a titanium aluminide alloy outer casing and high-impact, temperature resistant plastics for many of its internal parts.[1] The M41A is fully sealed against corrosion, dirt and moisture and its electronics are hardened against TREE and background radiation, making it perfectly usable even in a vacuum.[2] By itself the rifle weighs only 3.2 kg, although this increases to 4.9 kg when including the sling and fully-loaded magazine, and is built around a 24.7 cm long barrel.[3]

The M41A uses an electronic pulse action to fire, controlled directly from the trigger. The internal mechanism, including the rotating breech, is mounted on free-floating rails within a carbon-fiber jacket and the entire assembly is recoil dampened to reduce the effects of muzzle climb during burst and fully-automatic fire.[1] Even so, the weapon's recoil is fairly significant.[4] A thumb selector allows the firer to switch between selective, four-round burst or fully automatic firing modes.[1] In the event of a stoppage, a manual cocking handle on the right hand side of the receiver allows the user to check for rounds in the chamber or clear the breech in the event of a stoppage. The standard M41A ammunition magazine stores 99 rounds in a 'U' bend conveyor. Rounds are fed mechanically into the weapon's rotating breech.[1] While the magazine weighs 1.5 kg when fully loaded,[3] standard practice is to only fill it to 95% capacity (95 rounds) to prevent jamming.[1]

The M41A usually mounts the underbarrel U1 Grenade Launcher,[5] comprising a barrel, breech and four-round internal magazine, fired using a trigger just in front of the rifle magazine, the housing for which doubles as a grip during grenade firing. While this launcher was integral to initial versions of the rifle, later models (specifically the M41A MK2) featured a modular system that allowed the launcher to be swapped out for a different unit at the user's discretion.[6] Grenades must be hand-loaded into the launcher's four-round magazine, which are then loaded into the breech and primed to fire from a pump action.

Limited Distribution Firearms (Non-Cataloged)
The Browning firearms within this classification are from a unique, special category of firearms which may not appear in current or past Browning catalogs.

title: For Sale:   Winchester Model 1894 Pre 64 Rifles Winchester Lever Pre 64 Rifles
postcontent:
This isn't just any 1894! A special order gun with half round half oct bbl, button mag and checkered pistol grip deluxe. Cal 30 WCF. A very fine condition gun with nearly all blue remaining on both frame and bbl. The only wear is near the serial number at the carry point a little bit on the bottom. Blue has flaked on the upper tang. The wood is also exceptional. As stated, this is a deluxe and has beautiful deluxe wood. Equipped with rifle style butt. Wood is nice fitting with orig varnish. Now more about Sheriff Hodge. Engraved on the left side of the gun is " Sheriff Bob Hodge Seattle 1910". A little research on Sheriff Hodge shows that he was quite a controversial figure in early politics in the Seattle area. He had aspirations to be a politician and made a lot of enemies. He was a very colorful figure who was arrested once and released almost immediately. He sought re-election and won. The people loved him but opposing politicians didn't. This gun is a wonderful condition gun that would add to any collection and has an interesting history.
